Reading through the [can kernel docs](https://www.kernel.org/doc/Documentation/networking/can.txt) we could probably be more explicit here - checking the len(cf) is exactly what we expect.

>   Example:
>    [ remember: CANFD_MTU == sizeof(struct canfd_frame) ]

```
    struct canfd_frame cfd;

    nbytes = read(s, &cfd, CANFD_MTU);

    if (nbytes == CANFD_MTU) {
            printf("got CAN FD frame with length %d\n", cfd.len);
	    /* cfd.flags contains valid data */
    } else if (nbytes == CAN_MTU) {
            printf("got legacy CAN frame with length %d\n", cfd.len);
	    /* cfd.flags is undefined */
    } else {
            fprintf(stderr, "read: invalid CAN(FD) frame\n");
            return 1;
    }
```

The fact that we use [-1] twice suggests that this can be simplified. I think we should remove the line `last_body = node.body[-1]` and rename all occurences of "last_body" to "node" in the code below. This will probably make some tests fail. However, the current code doesn't handle all cases correctly either. For example, it fails if node doesn't have a field "body". I think the following code might be closer to what we're after (untested):

```
def _get_last_child(node):
    for name in ['finalbody', 'orelse', 'handlers', 'returns', 'body']:
        try:
            field = getattr(node, name)
        except AttributeError:
            continue

        if isinstance(field, list):
            if field:
                return field[-1]
        else:
            return field
    return None


def get_last_line_number(node):
    while True:
        last_child = _get_last_child(node)
        if last_child is None:
            return node.lineno
        node = last_child
```

This method should be updated to this:
``` python
def row_to_bbox_coordinates(row):
    """
    Takes a row and returns a dictionary representing bounding
    box coordinates:  (center_x, center_y, width, height)  e.g. {'x': 100, 'y': 120, 'width': 80, 'height': 120}
    """
    return {'x': row['xMin'] + (row['xMax'] - row['xMin'])/2, 'width': (row['xMax'] - row['xMin']),
            'y': row['yMin'] + (row['yMax'] - row['yMin'])/2, 'height': (row['yMax'] - row['yMin'])}
```
The previous code had a bug in it where `x` is the x origin and `y` is the y origin. `x` should actually be the center x, and `y` should be the center y of the bounding box. I also tried to add a comment in the documentation too because I thought this wasn't intuitive.

